<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Scirpus microcarpus </i>is a perennial bulrush that attains 1.5 m in height. Plants have a spreading habit due to long, reddish rhizomes. Aerial culms are leafy and ligules are present. The inflorescences are spikelets in headlike clusters (The Jepson Manual 2012). Water and birds disperse the achenes. Like other bulrushes, seeds remain dormant as long as they remain submerged, forming a seed bank. Germination and seedling establishment occurs when mudflats are not flooded. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Scirpus microcarpus</i> occurs in many wetland habitats throughout California. It typically grows in flooded, wet, moist or saturated meadows, stream edges, springs or swales. It can also be found in marshes, fens, pond margins, or as a common understory component of riparian forests. Water is usually fresh and not strongly alkaline or salty (Boul et al. 2021b). <br/>
<br/>
Coastal and tidal stands dominated by <i>S. microcarpus</i> are now placed in the <i>Carex obnupta - Oenanthe sarmentosa - Scirpus microcarpus</i> as of 2022. For the higher elevation stands, the USNVC (NatureServe 2021) defines an association of <i>Scirpus microcarpus</i> within a broader alliance designation of <i>Carex utriculata - Calamagrostis canadensis </i> alliance, found in California, Oregon, Washington, and Idaho. Stands can be monotypic but the great variety of habitats and elevations at which this vegetation occurs makes it difficult to prescribe species composition. In general, these stands are adjacent to deciduous or coniferous trees at the wetland periphery (NatureServe 2022). Potter (2005) considered both <i>S. microcarpus </i>and <i>S. congdonii </i>as ecological equivalents; he placed them in a bulrush alliance, which we treat as this montane association. Upon further analysis the montane type in California will be subsumed into a broader alliance designation. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
