    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af). One small stand identified in a seasonally inundated wetland at the southern end of Upper Crystal Springs Reservoir. Oak/madrone woodlands and stands of willow are nearby.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gi). One stand located in a riparian meadow east of West Valley Reservoir (Boul et al. 2021b)</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa, Ae, Ag-l). Stands with <i>Agrostis stolonifera</i> and <i>Argentina egedii</i> at Humboldt Bay National Refuge occur in managed wetlands (Pickart 2006). Small stands at Point Reyes National Seashore (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a) and inland in the Mount Tamalpais watershed (Evens and Kentner 2006) are surrounded by coastal scrub or other wetland herbaceous types, such as those of the <i>Carex obnupta</i> alliance. In stands of <i>Alnus rubra, Salix laevigata,</i> and <i>Salix lucida</i> ssp. <i>lasiandra</i> alliances, <i>Scirpus microcarpus</i> is regularly an understory dominant.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ee, Eh, Em, Ep-q). Stands, generally with <i>Glyceria elata, Oxypolis occidentalis,</i> and <i>Scirpus congdonii,</i> are found in meadows, along stream banks, and in seeps at montane elevations (Halpern 1985, Potter 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Df, Di-j, Dm). Stands at montane elevations contain <i>Epilobium ciliatum</i> and <i>Geum macrophyllum</i> (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands are small and restricted to wet, freshwater seeps and swales. Such stands in the Sierra Nevada occur on peat deposits and are indicative of high quality, sheetflow fens (Cooper and Wolf 2006). Further research is needed to evaluate stands throughout the state, better understand environmental relationships, and fine-scale composition and distribution patterns. </div>
</div>

    

    

